article.description:
Corliss Williamson scored four of his
19 points in the final minute of overtime as the Detroit Pistons
overcame Ricky Davis' 42 points to beat the Cleveland Cavaliers
109-107 Friday night.
article.headline: Davis scores 42 points in Cavaliers' OT loss
article.linkText: Pistons overcome Davis, Cavs to win sixth straight
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons have had quite enough of the Cleveland Cavaliers.
Williamson

Two days after an overtime victory in Cleveland, the Pistons had to do it again. Corliss Williamson scored four of his 19 points in the final minute of overtime as the Pistons overcame Ricky Davis' 42 points beat Cleveland 109-107 Friday night. "That team gives us a lot of problems,'' Pistons coach Rick Carlisle said. "I take my hat off to them -- they deserved to win these games just as much as we did.'' The Pistons have won a season-best six straight, while the Cavaliers have lost 13 consecutive road games. "Obviously, we are all frustrated,'' Zydrunas Ilgauskas said. "We're losing a lot of close games and now two in overtime. We always play hard, but as young as we are, it is always hard to get the results we want.'' Cleveland led by six in the final minute of regulation, but the Pistons rallied. Chucky Atkins' 3-pointer made it 98-97 with 12.8 seconds left. Davis hit two free throws, but Chauncey Billups took a pass from Richard Hamilton and hit a game-tying 3-pointer with 3.9 seconds left. The Cavaliers had intended to foul Billups and make the Pistons inbound the ball again, but failed. "We didn't have a timeout, so we wanted to get a foul and get the defense organized,'' Cleveland coach John Lucas said. "But that's part of the growing pains with a young team. We let this one get away.'' Billups scored eight points in overtime in the first game of the home-and-home series. "That was the second time he killed us,'' Davis said. "He stepped up and hit the big shot. We left him open and that's what he did.'' Davis missed the final shot of regulation, and Milt Palacio's apparent game-winning tip-in was ruled to have come just after the buzzer. Davis scored five points to help the Cavaliers go up 105-101, but Detroit came back to tie the game at 107 on two free throws by Williamson with 51.5 seconds left. Ben Wallace blocked Dajuan Wagner's drive, and Williamson hit a running hook over DeSagana Diop to give Detroit its first lead since the third quarter. "I just wanted to go strong to the basket and either score or draw a foul,'' Williamson said. "I knew that if the shot didn't drop, I needed to get to the line.'' Davis had an open jumper to tie, but passed to Jumaine Jones, who missed a game-winning 3-pointer at the buzzer. The Pistons, who had gone against their usual defensive philosophy and double-teamed Davis in overtime, were glad to see him pass up the last shot. "Ben was running at him and I was coming at him from behind, so it would have been a tough shot, but he had been making tough shots all night,'' Billups said. "I was very happy to see him dish that ball off.'' Hamilton led the Pistons with 27. Wallace added 11 points and 19 rebounds. Ilgauskas had 20 for Cleveland before fouling out late in regulation. Cleveland led 49-48 at the half behind 15 points from Ilgauskas. Neither team led by more by two points in the third quarter, and the Cavaliers needed 16 points in the period from Davis to take a 75-74 advantage into the final period. The lead was still one, 86-85, before Wagner scored five straight points to make it a six-point game with about four minutes left. First, he hit a long 3-pointer, then drove and flipped a high-arching shot over Wallace. Game notes
Wallace, who plays forward for the Pistons, has 411,325 votes at center to lead injured Dikembe Mutombo (288,325) and Ilgauskas (140,176) by wide margins in Eastern Conference All-Star voting. ... Wallace and Robinson picked up third-quarter technicals for arguing calls. ... The Pistons attempted 23 free throws in the third quarter, two short of the team record, but missed seven of them. ... Neither team led by more than four points until the fourth quarter. ... The Pistons hadn't played back-to-back overtime games since Jan. 11-12, 1991. ... Cavaliers guard Darius Miles missed the game with back spasms.
